/api/core/v1/types.go\\n- Line 5012: `type Pod struct`\\n- Line 5013: Pod embeds `metav1.TypeMeta`\\n- Line 21: Import alias defined as `metav1 \\\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\\\"`\\n\\nThis shows that Pod in the kubernetes/kubernetes staging area directly imports and embeds TypeMeta from the apimachinery package.\\n\\n**Step 2: Re-export Mechanism via kubernetes/api**\\n- Repository: kubernetes/api\\n- File: core/v1/types.go\\n- Line 21: Same import pattern - `metav1 \\\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\\\"`\\n- Line 5012-5013: Pod struct definition with identical TypeMeta embedding\\n\\nThe kubernetes/api module re-exports TypeMeta through direct transitive dependency on kubernetes/apimachinery. When code imports from k8s.io/api/core/v1, they gain access to TypeMeta through the metav1 alias, which points to k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1.\\n\\n**Step 3: Original TypeMeta Definition in kubernetes/apimachinery**\\n- Repository: kubernetes/kubernetes (contains apimachinery staging)\\n- File: staging/src/k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1/types.go\\n- Line 42: `type TypeMeta struct` - Original definition\\n- Line 49: `Kind string` field\\n- Line 56: `APIVersion string` field\\n\\nThe re-export chain works as follows:\\n1. kubernetes/apimachinery defines TypeMeta in pkg/apis/meta/v1\\n2. kubernetes/api imports directly from k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1, making TypeMeta available to consumers\\n3. kubernetes/kubernetes (main repo) staging area mirrors the api definitions, also importing from apimachinery\\n\\nThis design pattern ensures that TypeMeta, a foundational API type, is centrally defined in apimachinery and made available consistently across all Kubernetes API packages.\"\n}\n",
